# Testing Guidelines

Every piece of code must have accompanying tests. Tests should verify the behavior of the code being tested, not its dependencies. Use dependency injection (DI) to mock/fake dependencies.

## Core Principles

1. **Always write tests** - Every new feature, handler, use case, or service must have tests
2. **Test isolation** - Tests must not depend on external services or real implementations
3. **Mock dependencies** - Use DI container to inject fakes/mocks for all dependencies
4. **Test behavior, not implementation** - Focus on inputs/outputs and side effects

## DI Container for Testing

### Key Functions

```typescript
import { inject, register, reset } from '@trackit.io/di-container';
```

- `reset()` - Clears all registered dependencies (call at start of each test setup)
- `register(token, provider)` - Registers a dependency with the container
- `inject(token)` - Retrieves a registered dependency

### Provider Types

```typescript
// Value provider - for simple values or mock objects
register(tokenMyService, { useValue: mockObject });

// Class provider - for fake implementations
register(tokenMyService, { useClass: FakeMyService });

// Factory provider - for lazy instantiation
register(tokenMyService, { useFactory: () => inject(tokenFakeMyService) });
```

## Test File Structure

### File Naming

- Test files: `{ClassName}.test.ts`
- Mother classes (test data builders): `{ClassName}Mother.ts`
- Use case args mothers: `{UseCaseName}UseCaseArgsMother.ts`

### Standard Test Structure

```typescript
import { registerTestInfrastructure, tokenFake{Dependency} } from '@backend/infrastructure';
import { {Model}Mother } from '@backend/models';
import { token{UseCase}UseCase } from '@backend/useCases';
import { inject, register, reset } from '@trackit.io/di-container';

import { {ClassName} } from './{ClassName}';

describe('{ClassName}', () => {
  describe('{methodName}', () => {
    it('should {expected behavior}', async () => {
      const { className } = setup();

      // Arrange - set up test data using Mothers
      const input = {InputMother}.basic().build();

      // Act - call the method being tested
      const result = await className.{methodName}(input);

      // Assert - verify the result
      expect(result).toEqual(expected);
    });

    it('should throw {ErrorType} when {condition}', async () => {
      const { className } = setup();

      const input = {InputMother}.basic()
        .with{InvalidField}('invalid')
        .build();

      await expect(className.{methodName}(input)).rejects.toThrow({ErrorType});
    });
  });
});

const setup = () => {
  // Always reset and register test infrastructure first
  reset();
  registerTestInfrastructure();

  return {
    className: new {ClassName}(),
    fakeDependency: inject(tokenFake{Dependency}),
  };
};
```

## Mocking Strategies

### Strategy 1: Use Fake Implementations (Preferred for Infrastructure)

Use pre-built fake implementations that provide in-memory behavior:

```typescript
const setup = () => {
  reset();
  registerTestInfrastructure();

  // Get the fake repository to seed test data
  const fakeRepository = inject(tokenFakeMyRepository);

  return {
    useCase: new MyUseCaseImpl(),
    fakeRepository,
  };
};

it('should return the entity', async () => {
  const { useCase, fakeRepository } = setup();

  // Seed test data into the fake
  const entity = EntityMother.basic().build();
  await fakeRepository.save(entity);

  const result = await useCase.getEntity({ id: entity.id });

  expect(result).toEqual(entity);
});
```

### Strategy 2: Use vitest.fn() Mocks (Preferred for Use Cases in Adapters)

For handler/adapter tests, mock the use case entirely:

```typescript
const setup = () => {
  reset();
  registerTestInfrastructure();

  // Create mock use case
  const useCase = { methodName: vitest.fn() };
  useCase.methodName.mockResolvedValueOnce(
    ExpectedMother.basic().build(),
  );

  // Register mock with DI
  register(tokenMyUseCase, { useValue: useCase });

  return {
    adapter: new MyAdapter(),
    useCase,
  };
};

it('should call useCase with correct parameters', async () => {
  const { adapter, useCase } = setup();

  const event = MyAdapterEventMother.basic().build();
  await adapter.handle(event);

  expect(useCase.methodName).toHaveBeenCalledWith({
    // expected parameters
  });
});
```

### Strategy 3: Spy on Functions

For verifying internal function calls:

```typescript
import * as parseEventModule from '@backend/utils/parseEvent';

const setup = () => {
  reset();
  registerTestInfrastructure();

  const parseSpy = vitest.spyOn(parseEventModule, 'parseEvent');

  return { parseSpy, adapter: new MyAdapter() };
};

it('should call parseEvent with correct schemas', async () => {
  const { adapter, parseSpy } = setup();

  await adapter.handle(event);

  expect(parseSpy).toHaveBeenCalledWith(
    event,
    expect.objectContaining({
      paramsSchema: expect.anything(),
    }),
  );
});
```

## Mother Classes (Test Data Builders)

Use the Object Mother pattern with builder methods for flexible test data creation.

### Domain Model Mother

```typescript
import type { MyModel } from './MyModel';

export class MyModelMother {
  private data: MyModel;

  private constructor(data: MyModel) {
    this.data = data;
  }

  // Factory method with sensible defaults
  public static basic(): MyModelMother {
    return new MyModelMother({
      id: 'default-id',
      name: 'Default Name',
      createdAt: new Date('2025-01-01'),
    });
  }

  // Builder methods for each property
  public withId(id: string): MyModelMother {
    this.data.id = id;
    return this;
  }

  public withName(name: string): MyModelMother {
    this.data.name = name;
    return this;
  }

  public withCreatedAt(createdAt: Date): MyModelMother {
    this.data.createdAt = createdAt;
    return this;
  }

  // Build method returns the final object
  public build(): MyModel {
    return this.data;
  }
}
```

### Use Case Args Mother

```typescript
import type { MyUseCaseArgs } from './MyUseCase';

export class MyUseCaseArgsMother {
  private data: MyUseCaseArgs;

  private constructor(data: MyUseCaseArgs) {
    this.data = data;
  }

  public static basic(): MyUseCaseArgsMother {
    return new MyUseCaseArgsMother({
      id: 'default-id',
      user: UserMother.basic().build(),
    });
  }

  public withId(id: string): MyUseCaseArgsMother {
    this.data.id = id;
    return this;
  }

  public withUser(user: User): MyUseCaseArgsMother {
    this.data.user = user;
    return this;
  }

  public build(): MyUseCaseArgs {
    return this.data;
  }
}
```

## Test Categories

### 1. Validation Tests

Test input validation and error handling:

```typescript
describe('args validation', () => {
  it('should return 400 without required parameters', async () => {
    const { adapter } = setup();
    const event = EventMother.basic().build(); // missing params

    const response = await adapter.handle(event);
    expect(response.statusCode).toBe(400);
  });

  it('should return 400 with invalid UUID', async () => {
    const { adapter } = setup();
    const event = MyAdapterEventMother.basic()
      .withId('not-a-uuid')
      .build();

    const response = await adapter.handle(event);
    expect(response.statusCode).toBe(400);
  });
});
```

### 2. Business Logic Tests

Test the core functionality:

```typescript
describe('useCase and return value', () => {
  it('should call useCase with correct parameters', async () => {
    const { adapter, useCase } = setup();
    const user = UserMother.basic().build();

    const event = MyAdapterEventMother.basic()
      .withUser(user)
      .build();

    await adapter.handle(event);

    expect(useCase.method).toHaveBeenCalledWith({
      user,
      // other expected params
    });
  });

  it('should return 200 on success', async () => {
    const { adapter } = setup();
    const event = MyAdapterEventMother.basic().build();

    const response = await adapter.handle(event);
    expect(response.statusCode).toBe(200);
  });
});
```

### 3. Error Handling Tests

Test error scenarios and custom errors:

```typescript
describe('error handling', () => {
  it('should throw NotFoundError when resource does not exist', async () => {
    const { useCase } = setup();

    const input = MyUseCaseArgsMother.basic()
      .withId('non-existent-id')
      .build();

    await expect(useCase.method(input)).rejects.toThrow(NotFoundError);
  });
});
```

### 4. Edge Case Tests

Test boundary conditions and special cases:

```typescript
describe('edge cases', () => {
  it('should handle empty list', async () => {
    const { useCase, fakeRepository } = setup();
    // Don't seed any data

    const result = await useCase.getAll();

    expect(result).toEqual([]);
  });

  it('should handle backward compatibility when field is undefined', async () => {
    const { useCase, fakeRepository } = setup();

    const model = ModelMother.basic()
      .withOptionalField(undefined)
      .build();
    await fakeRepository.save(model);

    const result = await useCase.method({ id: model.id });

    expect(result.optionalField).toBeUndefined();
  });
});
```

## Fake Implementations

When creating new infrastructure services, always create a corresponding fake:

```typescript
// Port interface
export interface MyServicePort {
  doSomething(args: MyArgs): Promise<MyResult>;
}

// Real implementation
export class MyService implements MyServicePort {
  async doSomething(args: MyArgs): Promise<MyResult> {
    // Real implementation with external calls
  }
}

// Fake implementation
export class FakeMyService implements MyServicePort {
  // In-memory storage for testing
  public results: Map<string, MyResult> = new Map();

  async doSomething(args: MyArgs): Promise<MyResult> {
    return this.results.get(args.id) ?? defaultResult;
  }
}

// Tokens
export const tokenMyService = createInjectionToken<MyServicePort>('MyService');
export const tokenFakeMyService = createInjectionToken<FakeMyService>(
  'FakeMyService',
  { useClass: FakeMyService },
);
```

## Checklist for New Code

When creating new code, ensure:

- [ ] Test file created (`{ClassName}.test.ts`)
- [ ] Mother class created for test data if needed
- [ ] `setup()` function uses `reset()` and `registerTestInfrastructure()`
- [ ] All dependencies are mocked/faked (not real implementations)
- [ ] Tests cover: validation, business logic, error handling
- [ ] Tests use Mothers for test data (not hardcoded objects)
- [ ] Tests verify behavior, not implementation details
